snippet.textDisplay: I am not wholly an advocate for either a vegan or omnivorous diet. However, do not be persuaded by lacking or often misinformation about these diets. A vegan diet can be dangerous when not done properly, but often these effects only 'kick in' over a more long term basis. A time period of a month often will not showcase these negative aspects. I would recommend watching Joe Rogans podcast with Chris Kresser on this topic as he gives a relatively unbiased and balanced overview on plant based diets. It is clear that the best diet would be based on organic foods including meat, fish and vegetables whereby all benefits from the plants can be experienced as well as benefits from meat. The comparison between these diets is highly flawed due to meat diets often being unhealthy consisting of processed or fast foods.

snippet.textDisplay:
In the end... Its a diet. It restricts dietary choices down to those which are high in many vitamins and nutrients while also promoting less processed/fatty foods. It in itself however is not magical. Meat/animal products if eaten in moderation and as part of a mainly plant based diet are healthy. The struggle with the vegan diet is finding enough calories and/or quality protien, especially if body building. Nothing wrong with the diet, just complicates things.

Vegans say that the vegan diet is going to give you so many health benifits, and as a whole vegans tend to be healthier... But that's in comparison to a western diet, which is undoubtedly pretty trash. If calories, micro/macronutrient intake is the same, there isn't a difference between vegan and plant based with the inclusion of animal products, with the exception one is much more limiting.
